â€¦Industrial Court Urges Federal Government to Appoint More Judges. President Muhammadu Buhari has pledged that his administration will continue to adequately fund the judiciary to enable it discharge its responsibilities. The President who spoke today at the commissioning of the annex building of the headquarters of the National Industrial Court of Nigeria (NICN), Area 3, Abuja, which also marked the valedictory session of the President of the Court, Justice Babatunde Adejumo said the Industrial Court Performance is crucial to ease of doing business in Nigeria. The President also said it is the collective duty of the three arms of government to collaborate so as to ensure fair justice delivery and safeguard the rights of all Nigerians.  Justice Babatunde A. Adejumo speaking earlier decried inadequate funding of the judiciary, infrastructure deficit and low human capital resources. He noted that the issue of delay in justice is due to insufficient Judges adding that only 1200 Judges are available in the country as he sought the President's approval for the Chief Justice of Nigeria (CJN) to appoint more judges across board to ensure justice is delivered without delay. Justice Adejumo while commending the President for the increase in funding from N73billion before this administration to N100billion however requested N150billion in the 2020 budgetary provisions.  Our Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan reports that the Chief Justice of Nigeria, Justice Ibrahim Tanko while calling for more support to the judiciary said with improved budgetary allocation to the Judiciary more can be achieved. 